text: Anyone else getting an "E.T." vibe from this trailer? If someone had told me that this was directed by Steven Spielberg or J.J. Abrams (who directed "Super 8" which felt very much like a Spielberg film), I would believe them. Looks like David Lowery is certainly someone to keep an eye on as this film looks visually stunning. It's no wonder that they are entrusting him with Disney's future "Peter Pan" live-action adaptation. I'm liking the small nods to the original with the phrase "I Saw A Dragon" at the end, and the capture of Elliot. I could almost see this as more of a sequel to "Pete's Dragon" seeing as it takes place in a modern Pacific Northwest forest as opposed to the coastal town of Passamaquoddy, Maine in the early 19th century. Lest we forget, at the end of the original film Elliot left to help another kid in trouble. I hope the film includes nods to the songs that won't be included, or that "Candle On The Water" at least be played during the end credits. So far, this looks to be a fun family adventure at any rate. :) 

text: Definitely got that Jungle Book vibe again. At least Elliot still looks "cute," as he's supposed to, despite being more "realistic" than the original cartoonish purple Elliot. (I feared they'd try and make him look like one of Daenerys' dragons, in an effort to make a "darker and more serious" film. xD) Looks as though they went the more middle-ground, How-to-Train-Your-Dragon-esque route. Can't help feeling that the first Elliot will have more personality and this'll be another by-the-numbers, forgettable, uninspired story. I guess it has a little potential, but honestly, this is what I'd been expecting Brave to be: adults gang up on child's/teen's "dangerous" animal friend, like Gaston's angry mob on the Beast...main character and allies have to protect it from those who don't understand it...yadda.

text: there are many ways Disney could screw this up, but I swear if they focus too much on the wrong thing I'll be over it's live action movies. if they want us to "discover the wonder" of this movie they're giving us, then they should study the older movies, like snow white, Cinderella and Peter Pan. they have been SO focused on "we need to make these older things look new and cooler!" need proof? watch Jungle Book. it's forty percent focused on the story, which isn't very good in Disney standards, and sixty on CGI and "bringing these characters to life". TOO. MUCH. NOT CARING ABOUT IMPORTANT THINGS.  I swear Walt Disney is turning in his grave over new Disney movies. if you look back at his old movies, they are SOOOOOO different from newer ones. take Cinderella for instance. a girl who's misunderstood by her family gets what she's always wished for at a price. it's a story we've seen a million times, even back when it was made, but it works! why? because Walt Disney didn't focus too much on making the movie so appealing to certain audiences or about remaking things. he cared about showing only the people who had an actual reason to be there. the things we saw in those older movies, in a characteristic perspective, were things that no one had ever seen before, and were interesting, magical, and important. think of any old movie made by Disney himself. now think of characters in that movie who didn't have a reason to be there. mind blown. If new Disney wants to make a movie, and I mean the first fantastic one they've made in a long time, they need to go in the opposite direction of where they're going now. DO NOT focus on bring old characters into the 21st century. sure it looks and feels cool but it doesn't last. it's like making a new candy, and then making a smoothie version. it lasts way longer, and you can enjoy it long term instead of just eating it, and being done. no one above the age of sixteen cares about old being rethought. absolutely no one.

text: Personally this just disappoints me.   Looking at the dragon itself it's... er... not too well designed and is something a kid would come up with after watching HTTYD and playing a game of Halo. "An amphibious dragon with active camo!!!11"  Other than that I already know the plot:  They discover a "lost child" who's been gone for X years and finally comes back to civilization. Shock! Awe! He couldn't POSSIBLY have survived out in the wilderness on his own(Plothole btw)! Wait, what's that? He was raised by a DRAGON!?  And from there the sequence of events that unfold in these movies: Somebody either thinks it's too dangerous OR wants to utilize it as weapon, they enter a conflict stage where the human people try to get the "bad guys" off it's back, showdown stage where they almost capture it, but the dragon escapes thanks to the boy's miraculous control over the dragon. Bad guy is killed, falling bridge style, and they all live happily ever after.  Honestly they've been rehashing this same plot throughout their recent movies, and I guarantee it'll happen with BFG.

text: The original Pete's Dragon was just an awesome movie all-around, and there isn't a chance in hell this film captures the same tone and spirit. ¬†It was one of the first movies I ever saw growing up in the 80's, and is one of my favorite movies, childhood or otherwise. First off, the film was truly scary, since the stakes were literally as high as they could be for both Pete and Elliott. Pete was being pursued by a crazy inbred family that wanted to go back to beating and torturing him as a slave, and Elliott was being hunted by a scary film-flam artist that wanted to kill him and use all his body parts for tonics and potions! As for the music, every song is a classic, or at the very least well constructed, and I remember them as well as any other Disney classic. But the real star was Elliott, who absolutely felt a million times more real than this misguided CGI fur-beast.

text: I also grew up on the older version as a kid.  And I, for one, am still genuinely excited to see this remake.  Guys, it's okay for a story to be re-interpreted as long as its essence and its heart remains the same, and I really think we're going to see that here.  The Jungle Book was *excellent.*  Have a little faith <3  Also, I'm a total dragon nerd but I'm personally psyched to see a fluffy dragon.  It doesn't have to be fur when feathers or pseudo-feathers are a possibility as well.  There are so many scaley firebreathing lizards out there while softer/feathered beauties like the coatyl go unnoticed and unloved.  At the very least, this movie's doing more than Jurassic World did.

text: Dragon with hair?Really?Cos kids like teddy bears?Kids are young not stupid. Epic concept fail.

Sweet, charming, colorful and gorgeous this is again one of the big hits from disney this year. This film is truly representation of family entertainment and it just has that 90s vibe to it being simple, short and modest, but also having a huge heart and great dragon as protagonist. Filmmakers did a fine job in giving this dragon life, personality and his character just shines in this film and you can't help but to fall in love with him. Young Pete was also charming young actor and supporitng cast does a nice job, it is very clean, some will say ecological film with great visuals, cinematography and score. Film may  end up looking cliche and recycled, but execution is what matters and in my opinion they created another christmas classic sure to be played during the holidays in the future. 3.5/5

THIS MOVIE, in other cases, was one of the MOST AWFUL THINGS from 2016, it's just completely FUCKED BEYOND BELIEVE. Seriously, if you actually want to watch a actual GOOD remake or reboot of a movie, I request you probably watch Shin Godzilla.
